<DOC><DOCNO> AP890208-0011 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 0119EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-BRF--SAfrica-Unionist     02-08 0143</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--SAfrica-Unionist,0145</SECOND><HEAD>Leader of Black Labor Federation Denied Passport</HEAD><DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The general secretary of thecountry's largest labor federation was denied a passport to go toZimbabwe for a conference dealing with sanctions on South Africa,the federation says.   The Congress of South African Trade Unions, a predominantly blackfederation that actively opposes apartheid, said Tuesday that JayNaidoo submitted an urgent passport application on Jan. 5 in hopesof attending this week's conference in Harare.   Representatives of eight Commonwealth countries are meeting todiscuss ways of intensifying pressure on South Africa'swhite-dominated government to dismantle its system of racialseparation.   The federation said it received no response to Naidoo'sapplication despite two letters and four telephone calls to theDepartment of Home Affairs. The department refuses to disclosereasons for its decisions on passport and visa applications.</TEXT></DOC>